{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/0028060169A/1938020901/0670.xml":{"full_text":"West Virginia Executive Is\nChosen at Columbia Con\nference Here.\nBy EDWARD C. STONE.\nAt the concluding session of the\nColumbia Regional Conference of\nCredit Bureau Executives at the May\nflower Hotel these officers were elected\nfor 1938: George R. Parsons. Fair\nmont, W. Va.. president; N. D. Bartle,\nSyracuse, N. Y., vice president; William\nBush, Greensburg, Pa., secretary-treas\nurer.\nThe following were elected directors;\nJohn K. Althaus, Washington, D. C.;\nA. B. Buckeridge, New York City;\nFrank Cline, Salisbury, Md.; C. Guy\nFerguson, Pittsburgh; D. H. Penn,\nDanville, Va., and Paul Echeverria,\nMorristown. N. J\nThe meetings yesterday were fea\ntured by an address by Dr. N. H. Engle\nof the Bureau of Foreign and Domestic\nCommerce on the subject \"Activity in\nConnection With Shortening of Credit\nTerms.\" The speaker at the lunch\neon was Frank T. Caldwell of St.\nLouis._secretary and general manager\nof the Associated Credit Bureaus of\nAmerica.\nMr. Parsons, the new president, has\nbeen very active in the regional con\nference work. The convention is the\nmost important of the year held in\nthis territory.\nMcKee Notes 73d Birthday.\nH. H. McKee, president of the Na\ntional Capital Bank and also of the\nEast Washington Savings Bank,\nreached his 73d birthday anniversary\ntoday. Somehow the news got noised\nabout among his close personal friends\nin the financial district and he re\nceived a hast of congratulations by\nletter and phone and many flowers.\nMr. McKee has been head of the\nNational Capital Bank for 21 years,\nhaving been elected to the office on\nJanuary 11, 1917. A trustee in the\nEast Washington Savings Bank, he\nassumed the presidency on the death\nof John C. Yost three years ago.\nHe has been a leader in the District\nBankers\u2019 Association longer than the\naverage banker can recall, has ad\ndressed a host of conventions and\nserved on many of the most important\ncommittees.\niu yuuuga uays lie a vny\nImportant figure in the American\nBankers\u2019 Association and often ap\npeared on the programs at national\nconventions. Rated as one of the best\ninformed bankers in the Capital, he\nIs frequently consulted whenever per\nplexing banking problems arise. Only\nthe other day he was re-elected chair\nman of the Washington Clearing\nHouse Association for another term.\nConvention Officers Meet\nThomas J. Groom, president of the\nDistrict Bankers\u2019 Association, will en\ntertain the other association officers\nend committee chairmen who are ar\nranging for the annual convention, at\nhis residence at the Westchester this\nevening. The meeting is to perfect plans\nfor the Hot Springs meeting. T. Stan\nley Holland being the general chair\nman.\nThe Friday luncheon of members of\nthe District Bankers\u2019 Association at\nthe Willard Hotel will be devoted to\nconsideration of the Federal Housing\nAct as amended. Francis G. Addison,\nJr., president of the Security Savings\nCommercial Bank, who has given\nthe matter special study, will lead the\ndiscussion.\nThe Publicity Committee of the\nDistrict Bankers\u2019 Association met to\nday with Chairman Sidney F. Talia\nferro at the Riggs National Bank to\nmake plans in connection with news\nmatter for the June convention at Hot\nSprings.\nBusiness Outlook Viewed.\nWhile business conditions in Mary\nland and Virginia in the first half of\n1938 are unlikely to equal the first\nhalf of 1937. yet the results are ex\npected to exceed the three-year aver\nage by a good margin, according to a\nsurvey just completed by the Brook\nmire Economic Service.\nThe forecast estimates that con\nsumer income in Maryland in the first\nsix months of 1938 should be 7 per\ncent better than the three-year aver\nage, although perhaps 9 per cent under\nlast year in the same period.\nBusiness in Virginia, based on con\nsumer income, is given a forecast of\n6 per cent better than the three-year\naverage, but 8 per cent under' the\n1937 mark.\nThe review states that the 1937\nfourth quarter reports showed bank\ndebits in Maryland were 20 per cent\nbetter than in the previous year, life\ninsurance was up 8 per cent, electric\nproduction 20 per cent, building 39\nper cent, pay rolls 1 per cent, auto reg\nistrations off 15, farm income up 13,\ngasoline consumption up 3, and a 14\nper cent drop in the number of\nfailures.\ncompared with the fourth quarter of\n1936, Virginia reported a drop of 1\nper cent in bank debits. 4 per cent in\nlife insurance, 1 per cent in electric\nproduction, but a gain of 39 per cent\nin building, 3 per cent in pay rolls, a\ndrop of 13 per cent in auto registra\ntions, a gain of 7 per cent in farm in\ncome. A drop of 3 per cent in gasoline\nconsumption was reported and a high\ner number of business failures.\nOffice Help Demand Rising.\nBusiness demand for new' office and\nclerical help has turned upward in\nmany localities since January l, after\ndropping precipitously all over the\ncountry during the last two months of\n1937, according to a survey of business\ncollege employment departments in\n95 large and small cities.\nThe survey, conducted by North\nwestern National Life Insurance Co.,\nIndicated that the total volume of new\nclerical jobs available in January,\n1938, was much lower than in Janu\nary of 1937, however, and considerably\nunder the employment demand of last\nautumn.\nWashington reported that office em\nployment demand here is equal to that\nof a year ago and is on the increase,\nwith calls coming chiefly from life in\nsurance and real estate firms, hotels,\nattorneys\u2019 offices and for congressional\nsecretaries.\nHeard in Financial District.\nRobert V. Fleming, president of the\nRiggs National Bank, will b? the guest\nspeaker representing the Business Ad\nvisory Council on the Department of\nCommerce program, \"Stories of Ameri\ncan Industry,\u201d over the Columbia net\nwork Saturday afternoon from 5 to\n5:30. Harry R. Daniel of the Com\nmerce Department will relate the story\nof \"American Home Building.\u201d\nAlbert S. Gatley, vice president of\nthe Lincoln National Bank, has just\nreturned from a month\u2019s visit at\nvarious Florida resorts.\nCapital Traction 5s maintained their\nrecent strength on the Washington\nStock Exchange today, again selling\nat 70.\nTRANSACTIONS ON THE NEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE\nBy Private Wire Direct to The Star.\n3:30 p.m.\nPrev. 1938 Stock and Sales\u2014 Net\nHigh. Low. Dividend Rate. Add 00. High. Low. Close, ehge.\n52 38 Acme Steel (4)_ 2 40 40 40 +1\n10* 814 Adams Exp (.SOg) 6 9 8* 8* V4\n23 19* Addressograph 1.40. 6 20* 20* 20*\n58V* 46* My Reduction (la). 11 49* 48* 48*\n1* 1 Air-Way El Appl___ 1 1* 1* 1*\n13* 10* Alaska Jun (.SOa).. 26 12* 12* 12*\n1* 1* Alleghany 7 1* lVi 1*\n17* 11* Alleg $30 ww _ 4 13* 12* 12*\n17* 12 Alleg pf no ww_ 1 12 12 12\n17* 12* Alleg pf xw _ 1 12 12 12\n17* 13* Alleg prior pf _ 1 13* 13* 13*\n21* 15* Alleghany Steel 10 l\u00aba* 16 16*+\n176* 154* Allied Chem (6a).\u2014 7 163 161* 161* -2\n9* 8 Allied Kidd)._ 2 8 8 8\n9'\u00bb 6* Allied Stores 20 7* 6* 7\n53* 43 Allied Strs pf (5)... 7 43 42 42 -1\n61* 38 Allis-Chalm 3.50g._ 28 44* 42* 42*-\n15* 11* Alpha Port Com (1) 2 13* 18 13V. +1\n3* 2* Amal Leather 2 2* 2* 2*\n15* 11 Am Bank Note .25e. 3 13* 13 13\n42* 80* Am Brake Sh 3.40g_. 6 36* 36 36\n82* 70* Am Can (4)- 6 81 80 80\n27* 19* Am Car&Fy ,25g__. 11 23* 22* 22*+*\n50 37 Am Car Fy pf 4g.. 2 41 40 40*+3*\n17* 12* Am Chain (l.SOg)\u2014 6 14* 14* 14*-*\n101 95 Am Chicle (4a)- 1 100 100 100 +1\n8 6 Am Colortyp*- 1 6* 6* 6Vi\n13* 10* Am Cornel Alco ,50g 1 U* in* 11*\n16* 13* Am Crys Sug ,50e... 4 14 13* 18*-*\n4* 8* Am Encaustic Til... 6 4* 4* 4*\n4* 8 Am Foreign Pwr.. 2 3* 3* 3*\n19 12 Am For Pw $6 pf.. 3 13* 13* 13*\n24 16* Am For Pw $7 pf.. 2 17 17 17\n11* 7* Am For Pwr 2d pf.. 1 8* 8* 8* +1*\n21 10 Am Hawiian SS la 1 io* 10* 10*+*\n4* 3 Ain Hide Leather. 4 3* 3 31,\n26 