 Wilson* Co pf (6). 2 50 494 50 _ 1\n19', 13 Woodward Iron 3 15'- 15 151. -1\n43*, 36 Woolworth (2.40) x 11 424 41*. 414 -4\n194 14H Worthington Pump 5-17 16', 164 4\n94 6.1 Wright Aero (2g)__ 70s 76 75 75 -4\n65 62 Wrigley (3a)- 2 66 65 66 -24\n154 84 Yellow Truck _ 140 144 134 13',- 1,\n*3*\u2018 fl\u00bb4 YgstwnS*T3.2og.. 36 364 35',\u2018 354 -4\n224 15 Ygstwn Stl Dr .25e. 7 17*. 164 164 -4\n.174 12 ZenithRadio_ 15 134 134 13',-*,\n34 2*, Zonite Products_ 7 34 3*, 34 1,\nApproximate Soles of Stocks on the N. Y. Stock Exchange.\n11:00 A.M- 290,000 12:00 Noon_ 410 000\n1:00 P.M.... 500.000 2:00 P.M.. SSoioOO\nActual sales: unit of trading 30 shares\nB.nkrnU,--n\u00bbV.UPICJr or. r?f:>v*r*hip or being reorganized under\nBankruptcy Act. or securities assumed by such companies\nRates of dividends in ihe foregoing table are annual dis\nI JViVi*enrVn l\u00ae *,assd on. 'he last Quarterly or semi-annual declara\ninc\"iidednle5! otherwise noted or extra dividends are not\nk Ex dividend, xr Ex rights, a Also extra or extras h 1-1(1\nshare of SC preference stock d 1-25 share of $3 preference\nDfdattd or paid so far this year f Payable0 m stock*\norPdeclared \u201d1s'yearC*Sn \u00b0r St0Ck' k Accumulated dividend paid\nHEARINGS RESUMED\nON PLANS FOR MONON\nBy the Associated Press,\ni The Interstate Commerce Commis\nsion resumed hearings yesterday on\nthe reorganization plan of the Chi\ncago, Indianapolis A Louisville\n(Monon) Railroad.\nH. C. Howard and W. P. Starr of\nthe commission's finance bureau sub\nmitted a tentative plan for segregation\nof earnings and expenses of mortgaged\nlines in the Monon system. The pur\npose of the plan, they said, is to help\ndetermine the treatment to be received\nby holders of various securities in re\ncapitalizing the railroad.\nThe Monon is jointly controlled by\nthe Louisville A Nashville and South\nern Railroads.\nBUSINESS ADVICES.\nBy the Associated Press.\nBusiness advices to the Commerce\nDepartment from representatives\nabroad include:\nJapan\u2014January exports 17 per cent\nlower, imports 35 per cent lower, com\npared same month previous year.\nPhilippines\u201493,000,000 peso road\nprogram proposed by President.\nTurkey Last quarter conditions\nfairly satisfactory.\nChile\u2014Wholesale trade in Santiago\narea stagnant.\nLIVE STOCK CO-OP ELECTS.\nBALTIMORE, Feb. 9 <*>).\u2014The\nEastern Live Stock Co-Operative Mar\nketing Association yesterday re-elected\nThomas B. Glascock, Upperville, Va.,\npresident, and R. H. Tuckwiller, Lew\nisburg, W. Va., vice president. F. L.\nMiles, manager of the association, re\nported that live stock prices in 1937\nreached the highest point in years,\nthen went into a \u201ctailspln.\u201d\nCUBA SHIPS LESS SUGAR.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 9 G4>).\u2014Cuban\nexports of sugar from January 1 to\nFebruary 5 totaled 316,599 long tons,\nraw value, compared with 339,348\ntons in the comparable 193t period,\naccording to Havana cable* to Lam\nborn A Co.\nIngot Production Continues\nat 31 Per Cent of\nCapacity.\nBy the Associated Press.\n.NEW YORK. Feb. 9\u2014Steel ingot\nproduction this week is running at 31\nper cent of capacity, unchanged from\nlast week. Iron Age said today in its\nweekly review of the steel industry.\n\u201cEfforts by steel producers and con\nsumers to appraise the effect on busi\nness of this week's negotiations on a\nwage contract by the United States\nSteel Corp. and the S. W. O. C. so\nfar have not been fruitful,\u201d the pub\nlication reported.\n\u201cWhile some orders, held up by\nprice and wage uncertainty of recent\nweeks, are expected to materialize\nshortly, the industry is already look\ning for other developments to restore\nconfidence.\n\u201cSteel companies following the Steel\nCorp.\u2019s lead a year ago in making\nsigned agreements covering wages and\nother conditions of work are ex\npected to do likewise this year, with\nsome of the larger independent pro\nducers continuing to stand firm\nagainst such agreements.\n\u201cOvershadowed by interest in the\nwage negotiations are other develop\nments indicating that the period of\nhesitancy is not over,\u201d the organ\nadded.\n\u201cReflecting continued low melting\nrates, scrap prices, after holding for\nfive weeks, Mve again turned down,\nwith prime heavy melting steel off\n35 cents at Chicago, where other\ngrades dropped from 50 cents to $1\na ton.\n\u201cWith weakness at other centers,\nexcept in export classifications at\nPhiladelphia, the Iran Age com\nposite price (on avenge of Pittsburgh.\nChicago and Philadelphia prices) was\nlowered by 8 cents to $13.92.\nWith tower scrap quotations and\nan unchanged rate of ingot output,\nthe steel industry finds its principal\noutlets still operating on recent low\nproduction schedules, it was pointed\nout. Auto, railroad and buliding com\npany purchases of steel continue light.\nCOTTON TRADING HITS\n2,489,500-BALE MARK\nBy the Associated Press.\nThe Commodity Exchange Admin\nistration reported yesterday that Jan\nuary trading In cotton on the New\nYork and New Orleans Cotton Ex\nchanges and the Chicago Board of\nTrade totaled 2.489.500 bales.\nApproximately 82 per cent of the\ntrading was reported on the New\nYork exchange. 17 per cent on the\nNew Orleans market and the balance\nin Chicago.\nTotal open futures contracts aver\naged 3,570,294 bales daily for the\nthree markets, or 169,100 bales less\nthan in December.\nOHIO BRASS COMPANY\nENDS CHAIRMANSHIP\nBy the Associated Press.\nMANSFIELD, Ohio, Feb. 9.\u2014The of\nfice of chairman of the board of the\nOhio Brass Co. has been abolished,\nthe company announced today after\nthe annual meeting of directors.\nFrank S. Black, company founder,\nwas chairman from 1928 until he died\nlast December 19. Company spokes\nmen said C. B. King had been re\ntained as president.\nKing reported company\u2019s 1937 net\nprofit was $1,159,842, compared with\n$918,261 in 1936.\nDIVIDEND IS ORDERED.\nNEW YORK, Fbb. 9 (^.\u2014Direc\ntors of New York Air Brake Co. yester\nday ordered a dividend of 25 cents a\nshare on capital stock, payable March\n1 to holders of record February 18.\nIn 1937 company p$ld four dividends\nof 50 cents each.\nn\nPUSH STOCKS UP\nSome Profit Taking Curbs\nTrading But Slightly.\nRails, Steels Gain.\nStock Averages\n70 IS 15 50\nIndust. Ralls. OtlL Stocks.\nNet change. +.6 +.5 +.1 4-.4\nToday, noon 63.8 18.9 31.0 44.2\nPrevious day 63.2 18.4 30.9 43 8\nMonth ago.. 67.5 21.4 34.9 47.7\nYear ago...100.3 42.0 52.1 73.5\n1938 high_ 68.2 21.6 34.9 47.9\n1938 low... 59.2 17.6 30.0 41.3\n1937 high\u2014101.6 49.5 54.0 75.3\n1937 low_ 57.7 19 0 31.8 41.7\n1932 low_ 17 5 8 7 23.9 16.9\n1929 high\u2014146.9 153.9 184.3 157.7\n1927 low- 51.6 95.3 61.8 61.8\n(Compiled by the Associated Press.)\nBy VICTOR EUBANK,\nAssociated Press Financial Writer.\nNEW YORK. Feb. 9\u2014The stock\nmarket rallied fractions to a point or\nmore today, but profit selling stepped\nin near the final hour to nip some\ngains and transfer others into small\nlosses.\nVolume picked up on the extension\nof yesterday's recovery, but dri^d up\nas prices slipped off from their best.\nRails, steels, motors, farm equip\nments and building materials were\nprominent on the upturn. Later Steels\nand motors yielded to pressure and\nother leaders joined them In the\nminus column.\nHolding advances\u2014highs were shaved\n\u2014were Santa Fe. Great .Northern,\nContinental Can. United States Gyp\nsum. Johns-Manville. Inland Steel and\nNational Steel. Off a bit from yes\nterday's close, after an earlier good\nperformance, were United States Steel,\nBethlehem. Chrysler, American Tele\nphone. J. I. Case, Douglas Aircraft and\nAnaconda.\nTransfers were at the rate of\nabout 800.000 shares\na iys. earnings report showing net\nat 41 cents a common share, against\n21 cents in 1936. helped to boost Radio\nCorp., which advanced a wid\" frac\ntion. Coppers slipped after fair gains\nin early trading. American Telephone\nwas hesitant.\nThe major commodities joined stocks\non the plus side. Bonds were higher.\nForeign markets displayed strength,\nalthough profit-taking caused some\nirregularity before the close.\nA reduction of $4 a ton in the price\nof some classes of steel products, the\nfirst of any consequence since early\nlast fall, caught Wall Street somewhat\nby surprise, as it had been thought\nthe present quotations would be main\ntained through this quarter at least.\nIt appeared to have little effect mar\nketwise.\nHope that the Interstate Commerce\nCommission would act soon on the\nmooted question of higher rail freight\nrates called forth demand for the\ncarrier shares. Farm equipment issues\nwere bolstered by anticipation of final\npassage soon of the pending agricul\ntural bill.\nAnother item of interest was an\nofficial estimate Congress might be\ncalled upon to appropriate an addi\ntional $250,000,000 to $500,000,000 for\nwork relief.\nNEW YORK COTTON\nB* the Associated Pres*.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 9 UP).\u2014Cotton\ncontinued its advance today as the\nHouse passed the conference report\non the farm bill, but trading was less\nactive owing to a disposition to await\nfurther action on the report tomor\nrow.\nMay. which had sold up to 8 86 and\nthen reacted to 8 78. recovered to 8 83\nafter the House Vote on the bill this\nafternoon Prices in midafternoon\nshowed net advances of 5 to 8 points.\nNew Orleans Cotton.\nNEW ORLEANS. Feb 9 iIPi.\u2014jCotton\nprices showed an initial gain of almost\nSo cents a bale here today, due to trace\nand commission house buying, but reacted\na few points later under realizing and some\nhedge selling.\nIn early afternoon the March option\ntraded at 8.8'.'. May at 8 93. July at 8 99\nand October at 9.98. or 4 to 6 points\nabove yesterday s close.\nExports today were 1.411 bales.\nCottonseed oil opened steady March.\n7.3fib: May. 7.4]b: July. 7.47b. September.\n7.50b. October. 7.55b. bBid.\nt\n\nCHICAGO GRAIN\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO Feb. 9\u2014Aided by fairly\ngood export business in United States\nwheat, totaling 500.000 bushels. Chi\ncago wheat prices moved upward a\ncent today, but then reacted some\nwhat.\nProfit-taking on the advance led to\nthe setbacks from the day's top level.\nUpturns of securities, together with\nunabated drought Southwest, were a\ngood deal responsible for wheat up\nturns.\nAt the close. Chicago wheat futures\nwere \u2019a-3* higher, compared with yes\nterday's finish. May 957/*-96. July,\n917g-92. corn off to 3* up. May\n597*, July 60%-Vi and oats Vs ad\nvanced.\nCHICAGO. Peb. 9 IJPI.\u2014Chicago BTlin\nfutures:\nWHEAT\u2014\nOpen. High. Low. Close\nMay _ 98 92\u00bb\u00ab PI\", 91\u2019,-98\nJuly _ 92 923\u00ab 91s, 91\u2019,-02\nSeptember __ 92 92s, 913, 91s,\nCORN\u2014\nMay _ _503, 89', 59\u00bb, 59\u2019.\nJuly _89s, 81 89\u00bb, 89 s,-3,\nSeptember __ 61', 614, 61*-, fli\",\nOATS\u2014\nMay _31\", _ _ 313.\nJuly __ _ 29', _ _ 29',\nSeptember 29', _ _ 29',\nSOY BEANS\u2014\nMay __ 1.95*', 1.0ft3; 1.05\u2019i 1.0,Vi\nJuly _ _ __ _ 1.04\nRYE\u2014\nMay _\nJuly _ i\nSeptember\nLARD\u2014\nMarch_\nMay_\nJuly _\nSeptember_\nBELLIES\u2014\nMay -_ __\nC,,h Wheat.\nCHICAGO. Peb. 9 i/P).\u2014Caeh\nNo. 3 red. 954,: No. 4 hard. 99: No. 3\nNorthern spring, l.oi. Com\u2014No. 3 mixed.\n574,: No. 2 yellow. 59-80; No. 3 white.\n50: No. 4. 57. Oats\u2014No. 1 white. 34\n34s i: No. 2. 34-344,. Rye\u2014No. 2.\n80'*-82. Soy beans\u2014No. 2 yellow. 1.04\u2019,.\nBarley\u2014Actual sales, 85-87: feed. 48-83.\nnominal: malting. 70-91. nominal. Timo\nthy seed. 2.90-3.00: red clover, 32.CO\n37. 00; sweet clover. 10.00-50.\nWINNIPEG. Peb. 9 UP).\u2014Wheat elosed\n4, higher: May. 1.294',-v,; juiy,\n1.21'i-3, Oata \u2018a higher. May. 29V,-Hi\nJuly, 46'/,.\nBaltimore Wheat.\nBALTIMORE. Feb. 9 OPi,\u2014Wheat. No. 3\nred winter, garlicky, apot. domestic.\n1.01'j; February, 1.01',.\nNew England\nFund\nProspectus on Request\nA. S. Goulben A Inc.\nWoodward Bid* NA. 2000\n\"l\"","height":"31244","width":"22424"}}
